ing=5 cellspacing=1><tr><td valign=top bgcolor=#213d87 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=#213d87 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uquath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/30/02 8:08:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple, Clear and Poweful</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> In America, we elect our representatives based upon how well we think they will represent us. If we are conservative Christian, then we vote for thus...Likewise if one is liberal atheist...That’s the beauty of a democracy. We get to vote for those whom (we hope) will have our best interest in mind and heart, but all the while maintaining our rights.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think a represenative's responsibility should be to represent the whole community that he/she is responsible for.  It is similar to a household with 3 kids (2 girls and 1 boy).  If you ask the kids to vote on what they want to do for fun, the boy may never get a chance to do something he likes since he is in the minority.  So parents will try to make sure his wishes are represented in some form (e.g. taking turns deciding).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Your not ramming atheism down my throat by not praying before a meeting any more then a Christian does by praying before a meeting.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is hard to justify a nonaction as ramming something down someone's throat.  But I do know what you mean.  Some nonactions can create awkward social situations (like not saying &quot;excuse me&quot; after belching).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There has to be 'morals' in law. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is where I have to disagree.  The problem is determining what are correct morals.  Some Christians do not believe that women should wear jeans.  Afghanistan is a country that placed a lot of 'morals' into its laws.  I think we have seen how destructive that can be in the long run.<br>
<br>
Laws should be based on 'rights.'  Rape violates another person's rights.  So does murder and theft.  There is no need to appeal to morality to justify such laws.  What does become a sticky issue are laws designed to ensure the country's prosperity.  These are stuff like seat belt laws, establishing national laboratories and maintaining a military.  However, these types of laws can be easily be changed to morality laws when people are not watching.  States use these types of laws to determine who can marry, which should be a morality issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> However, at the same time I do not want my children to have to leave their religion and beliefs at the door. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't think anyone is trying to stop people from having a religion.  Like one of the prayer in school cases that went to the supreme court was based on a change of wording in the law.  The law use to say that there could be a quiet time for meditation.  They changed it to be a quiet time for meditation or religion.  The judges felt that there was already time for students to pray with the original wording.  The additional wording showed that the school was starting to push students to pray.<br>
<br>
Scott (Quath) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 736<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/30/02 10:04:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=42>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple, Clear and Poweful</span><hr size=1> <i>"Although some people do wear their religion like a hat, isn’t religion something that you take and have with you 24/7? There are two very familiar signs we see today...one is No Smoking and the other is No Concealed Weapons... What’s next, an R in a circle with a slash through it?"</i><br>
<br>
There is a difference between "wearing a religion" and being religious. Those who wear religion do so as a badge and flaunt it. Those who are religious need not prove to others their faith. They are content with being meek, showing humility rather than the pride those who tend to wear religion display.<br>
<br>
<i>"In America, we elect our representatives based upon how well we think they will represent us. If we are conservative Christian, then we vote for thus...Likewise if one is liberal atheist..."</i><br>
<br>
I am not so sure I follow the "conservative/liberal" dichotomy you present. In general, atheists tend not to follow any religion so can't be considered "religious liberals". Atheists can be politcally conservative as well as liberal. Christians can also vary in political alignment, too.<br>
<br>
However, I do follow your point on electing officials, but I wonder why one would want to elect an official on the basis of religious affiliation? After all, just because one is a professed Christian doesn't negate that the individual is actually a child molester, rapist, murderer, etc. I think you get the point.<br>
<br>
I also fully agree with Quath on this point. The best politicians are those who can represent all their constituents... even the atheist. After all, we atheists don't drink blood, or sacrafice babies. We tend to be very moral (more so than many professed Christians) and strongly promote liberty for all. Personally, I found but a couple Christians who promote liberty for all. Most Christians, in my experience, want to see government legislate from the morals of the Bible (of course, those they pick and choose from) and not from common sense, as Thomas Paine put it. <br>
<br>
<i>"There has to be 'morals' in law. There are many 'moral' laws that we can all agree with already that no one would want to change. Can anyone think of a few? These are more then "common sense" laws..Why is murder and stealing a crime?"</i><br>
<br>
Can you please explain why these are more than common sense laws? From my perspective we are all born without a religious faith, but with natures such that we are virtuous. After all, murder was frowned upon long before Judaism and Christianity were born. Somehow, people managed to live by laws for thousands of years without Judeo-Christian ethics. :)<br>
<br>
<i>"As far as prayer over the schools PA system, I am not for it. The reason is that I do not want my children to be 'pressured' into praying to a god that I do not approve of."</i><br>
<br>
Yes we agree. :) So, what is the difference then between that and a Senator praying into a microphone before a captive audience? I don't want my fellow countrymen and countrywomen pressured into praying to a god not of their choice. Again, such prayers are not protected by the Constitution. They are an abuse of power.<br>
<br>
<i>"There is alot of crap we do not want our children to watch and see. How do we fix it? We turn off the TV."</i><br>
<br>
Public prayers by elected officials (or paid public officials) before those who are not of a like minded faith is an abuse of power not protected by the constitution. Fellow senators can't just "change the channel" if one of their colleagues step up to the microphone and begin to pray to their God.<br>
<br>
I recall debating a Baptist minister over this very issue. He remarked that atheists, such as myself, should be grown up enough to accept the prayer and move on. I then asked him if he thought Jehovah's Witnesses were Christians. He said no. I then asked if he minded being forced to hear them pray to Jehovah. He was visibly flustered proclaiming that such a prayer is bothersome because it is to a false god. I asked this Baptist minister if he was narrow minded for believing that when Christians pray in public, then automatically all other faiths become illegitimate. Needless to say, he was not happy with logical reasoning on that score.<br>
<br>
The score is that those of a like minded faith will tolerate the public prayers of those supporting their own faith. God forbid that any other type of prayer be presented! It is with foresight that our founding fathers saw fit to seperate Church from the day to day affairs of running the government. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 741<br> <font color=#E9D756>(5/30/02 2:58:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=43>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Rheaton</span><hr size=1> I just wanted to post this reminder that I am not trying to prove you (or anybody <i><b>wrong</i></b>) and I don't feel that you are doing that, too. We all have our convictions and share them with passion, that is a good thing.<br>
