<br>
While I don't think we NEED public prayers I do feel the need to point out that Jesus never spoke against them.  In fact, as I recall he spoke against <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> not</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> pronouncing your beliefs to others.  Also somewhere in this thread someone asked what constituted an &quot;acceptable religion,&quot; and I believe I can answer that question.  An &quot;acceptable religion&quot; is one that does not advocate infringing on someone elses rights.  Even the constitution had this loop-hole. Freedom to excercise your rights without infringing on others.  I don't see praying in public as infringing on others rights, but I do see <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> refusing to allow people to pray in public</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> as infringing on their rights.  One can argue that by praying you are infringing on someones right to silence, but that isn't in the constitution.  The constitution doesn't protect silence, it protects speech. <p>________________________________________________________<BR><a href><font color=#CC90FF><i><b>"I am a Child of the Universe.  With a glitter of my life I travel through black, velvet space, and the gates of time.  I am a star awoken from it's sleep - by the longing cries of mankind's dreams.  Dreams of harmony, love, and a Child of the Universe."</b></i></font></a><BR>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<BR><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=165032"><img border="0" src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/jwebb2/Serenity.jpg" width="109" height="230"></a><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=164717"><img border="0" src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/jwebb2/Pickett.jpg" width="89" height="230"></a><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=165042"><img border="0" src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/jwebb2/Aphroditex.jpg" width="110" height="230"></a><BR>Click on a character to see their profile.<BR><a href><font face="