&gt; refusing to allow people to pray in public<br>
and Rheaton again<br>
&gt; One is not promised the right to not hear what they wish not to hear.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't want to ban praying in public. To me it's a matter of how one goes about it, and in particular, how the public is expected to interact with the prayer. The (mythical) baby eating Satanist should not be allowed to  practice &quot;religious&quot; rites in public (or private for that matter). I hope you would agree that a muslim should be allowed to kneel down and pray to Mecca in public, but it would not be appropriate to do it on a busy stairwell, nor to require everyone else on the train station to join in.<br>
<br>
Again, I think the matter has to be dealt with with considerable tact by public figures. If an elected representative of the people wishes to pray for guidance, that is ok. On the other hand I don't want to see prayers starting with &quot;We, the people of America..&quot; (or Australia as the case may be). I think what I'm saying is that I draw a distinction between public prayers, and prayers in public, and that the line comes into play when you are dealing with an official figure. This could also be a school principal.<br>
