</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulurikeen.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lurikeen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 767<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/1/02 10:36:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=59>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> <i>"This was more a lesson to teach praying for the correct reason than a lesson denouncing prayer in public."</i><br>
<br>
I agree. However, Jesus directed that when you pray "go into your room". Not my room, not our room, not outdoors in the town square... no, in <b><i>your</i></b> room. He is obviously saying that it is better to pray in private than to pray in public. Why? <i>Because</i> public prayers tend to become nothing more than puppeteering to the audience. Remember, Jesus said "And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, for they love to pray standing in the synagogues and on the street corners <b><i>to be seen by men</b></i>" Jesus is telling his followers not to pray in public for purposes other than conducting the business of their ministry. So, yes, Jesus speaks out against public prayers under certain conditions and tells his followers it is better to pray in private. It doesn't get much clearer than that.<br>
<br>
<i>"But in the excerpt it stated very clearly that the audience wasn't captive, it stated that many of the senators got up and walked out."</i> <br>
<br>
A "captive audience" is not one locked in a room, or chained to walls. A "captive audience" is one that assembles for some sort of business only to have it disrupted due to no choice of their own. Usually, the disruption is provided by a speaker who makes a presentation that was neither requested or planned.<br>
<br>
Besides, why the he<i></i>ll should I be put into a postion to have to leave a public gathering because some joker is abusing his power and authority? I take it, then, you would be all for a school principle chanting a Buddhist mantra over the PA system? Or, presenting a Baptist prayer over a PA system? The students could all get up and walk out, right?<br>
<br>
Or do you understand what it means for people of authority (especially public officials) to use their position of power and push their religious point of view onto those underneath them? That sort of coercion is flagrantly wrong. Yes, it is coercion. It is applying pressure upon those under you to bow their heads in prayer when in fact they don't want to.<br>
<br>
There are certain things we all can't do in public. Public officials should have enough guts (temperance) as to not wear their faith on their lapel. Idiotic prayers in the Senate will not make this country great. What will make it great is when the praying idiots in the senate stop lying to the public and actually do their damn jobs. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/urheaton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rheaton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/2/02 4:14:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Or do you understand what it means for people of authority (especially public officials) to use their position of power and push their religious point of view onto those underneath them? That sort of coercion is flagrantly wrong. Yes, it is coercion. It is applying pressure upon those under you to bow their heads in prayer when in fact they don't want to. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Is there such a thing as 'pushing religious' beliefs upon someone? I mean, is it really that great of an offense...or a offense at all? Most likely depends on the individual.<br>
<br>
I've heard that term many times in my life, and in some cases I would have to agree that some are zealots. But more then likely, if a Buddhist got up and started chanting his 'shaazams' over the PA or anywhere else, I would fall over laughing.<br>
<br>
Is the power and conviction of prayer so strong that it 'pressures' someone into guilt of obligation to bow their heads? Some forms of Christian religion promote raising ones hands and face, eyes wide open while speaking loudly and clearly to God. However, most of the time those prayers end with a Holy Ghost train formed and circling the room...talking about a 'captive audience'.<br>
<br>
Lurikeen, what kind of church did you attend when you were a wee lad and what was the turning point in your beliefs? I cant help but to think that at some point you were 'forced' to attend church.. Forgive me if ima wrong.<br>
